<article>

  <p>
    Most of a beginning sit is not calm. It is the mind leaving — into the next
    errand, the unfinished conversation, the itch to check whether the timer has
    moved — and then, occasionally, noticing that it has left. The instructions are
    almost insultingly plain. What makes sitting hard is that the mind treats those
    plain instructions as a bargain: produce stillness, earn a special state, or else
    the stretch “doesn’t count.”
  </p>

  <p>
    That bargain is the first confusion to drop. Sitting is one laboratory among the
    <a href="/concepts/three-trainings/">three trainings</a>
    — not the summit of the path. The
    <a href="/concepts/five-precepts/">precepts</a>
    and the rest of ethics still shape what arrives on the cushion; a regular sit gives
    attention fewer exits for a while. Breath and body frames in the
    <a href="/suttas/anapanasati/">Āṇāpānasati Sutta</a>
    and the
    <a href="/suttas/satipatthana/">Satipaṭṭhāna Sutta</a>
    develop that training later. This page is narrower: enough structure to begin
    without turning the beginning into a performance review.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Not a Special Mind</h2>

  <p>
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sati" data-en="mindfulness">Sati</span>
    is not a sharper commentary running on top of experience. It is not losing track
    of what is already appearing — including thoughts as they arise. Sitting does not
    manufacture that knowing by magic. It creates a stretch of time in which
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sati" data-en="mindfulness">sati</span>
    has a chance.
  </p>

  <p>
    Thoughts themselves are ordinary. What costs is being carried by them while the
    body sits as if something else were underway — planning, rehearsing, arguing,
    without noticing the carrying. Eyes closed and still lost in that current is not
    so much a failed sit as an unrecognized one. The first genuine skill is simpler
    and stranger: catching a thought as a thought while it is still present.
  </p>

  <p>
    That catching is active. It is steady interest in what is actually here — breath,
    pressure, sound, irritation, dullness — without needing to decorate it or flee it.
    Wanting a blank screen, or a guaranteed glow, turns the sit into a search for
    proof. Knowing what is given turns it into training.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Fewer Exits</h2>

  <p>
    Sitting still is not mystical. It is a temporary narrowing of the usual escapes —
    standing up, opening a screen, starting the next fix. Consider an ordinary
    afternoon: planning slides into memory, memory into irritation, irritation into the
    urge to rearrange something elsewhere. Off the cushion, each of those moves can
    recruit a new action. On it, they have fewer places to go. They become visible as
    moves.
  </p>

  <p>
    That visibility is why the sit earns its place beside ethics and daily heedfulness —
    not instead of them. In the
    <a href="/guide/">guide</a>
    arc, it follows view, precepts, and the second-arrow teaching — a laboratory among the
    three, not a starting gate that replaces them. The
    <a href="/concepts/practicing-off-the-cushion/">day remains the larger laboratory</a>.
    The cushion is a smaller one with clearer edges. Over time, meeting what appears
    there supports both stillness
    (<span class="pali" data-pali="samādhi" data-en="unification">samādhi</span>)
    and clear seeing. Worth holding lightly: walking, lying down, and ordinary tasks
    are fields for the same knowing. Start with the door that is easiest to keep open.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Conditions, Not Holiness</h2>

  <p>
    The body instruction is almost embarrassingly practical: upright enough to stay
    awake, relaxed enough to stay. Spine roughly vertical — not military rigidity, not
    a soft collapse. Hands in the lap or on the thighs. Eyes closed, or lightly open
    with a soft downward gaze if closing them pulls toward sleep. A chair is fine.
    Cross-legged on a cushion is fine. Kneeling on a bench is fine. The tradition does
    not grade seats by holiness.
  </p>

  <p>
    What matters is sustainability. Can the body remain for the planned time without
    injury and without constantly renegotiating the seat? Sharp or joint-threatening
    pain is a signal to adjust — not a test of discipline. Ordinary discomfort is
    different: an itch, a dull ache, the urge to shift again. Notice it the way one
    might notice a sound — present, known, not automatically obeyed. Comfort means
    the body can settle without fighting. Collapse means alertness has left. Aim for
    the first. The body itself —
    <span class="pali" data-pali="kāya" data-en="body">kāya</span>
    in the language of the foundations — is already a place to rest attention, not only
    a vehicle for getting the mind somewhere else.
  </p>

  <p>
    Short and regular beats long and heroic. Ten or fifteen minutes most days will
    teach more than an hour once, followed by a week of avoidance. Set a timer so
    attention does not have to keep auditing the clock. When every minute feels like a
    negotiation, shorten the sit rather than abandon the habit. Returning tomorrow
    matters more than winning today. Sleep deprivation and acute crisis are not the
    moments to force a long stretch. Ordinary reluctance usually is. The mind that
    waits for ideal conditions is often waiting forever.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Leave and Return</h2>

  <p>
    Choose a home base. For most beginners the breath at the nose, chest, or belly
    works well — the same territory the
    <span class="pali" data-pali="āṇāpānasati" data-en="mindfulness of breathing">āṇāpānasati</span>
    teaching develops in detail. The body as a whole — contact with the seat, the sense
    of uprightness — is another stable option. Pick one. Stay with it lightly, not
    clenched. The breath does not need to be improved. It needs to be known.
  </p>

  <p>
    The mind will leave. That is not a failure of the method; it is the method meeting
    an untrained mind. When wandering is noticed, return. No speech is required, but a
    quiet naming can help: “thinking,” “planning,” “sound.” Naming is not fighting.
    Fighting adds a second struggle on top of the first distraction — self-reproach
    piled onto ordinary mental noise. Returning without that story is the skill.
  </p>

  <p>
    Sometimes what pulls attention is denser than ordinary thought — desire, ill-will,
    dullness, restlessness, doubt. Those are the
    <span class="pali" data-pali="nīvaraṇa" data-en="hindrance">nīvaraṇas</span>,
    treated at length on the
    <a href="/concepts/five-hindrances/">five hindrances</a>
    page. For a starting sit, the instruction stays the same: know what is present,
    return when you can. The hindrances do not have to be cleared before the sit
    counts. Seeing them is already part of the work.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>What Counts</h2>

  <p>
    Success at the beginning is not a blank mind. It is not bliss. It is not a weekly
    chart of deeper
    <span class="pali" data-pali="jhāna" data-en="meditative absorption">jhānas</span>.
    Those measures turn practice into theatre — a search for proof that something
    special is happening. A sit spent mostly lost in planning, noticed a few times, and
    returned to — that is a successful sit. The return is the practice. The wandering
    is the field.
  </p>

  <p>
    Judging a sit by how pleasant it felt trains the mind to chase pleasant sits.
    Judging it by how still the mind became trains it to treat agitation as defeat. A
    sturdier measure is quieter: Did attention show up for the time set? Did it know,
    at least sometimes, what was happening? Did it return without turning the return
    into a verdict on character?
  </p>

  <p>
    There is a related trap around “acceptance.” Hoping the unpleasant will leave if
    one sits politely enough is still bargaining — a quieter form of struggle. Knowing
    an ache, an itch, or a wave of anxiety as something arising and changing is a
    different gesture. The first waits for better conditions. The second meets what is
    already here. The sit asks for the second, even when the body still needs ordinary
    care.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    "Just as the ocean has a gradual shelf, a gradual slope, a gradual inclination,
    with a sudden drop-off only after a long stretch, in the same way this Dhamma
    and Discipline has a gradual training, a gradual practice, a gradual progression,
    with a penetration to gnosis only after a long stretch."
    <cite>— Ud 5.5 / AN 8.19 (adapted)</cite>
  </blockquote>

  <p>
    When the timer ends, stop. Notice the body again for a moment. Carry whatever
    clarity there was — or whatever honesty about distraction there was — into the
    next ordinary task. The conditions for the next sit are mostly unglamorous: sleep,
    a clear enough schedule, and the decision not to wait for a better mood. Sitting
    is training, not theatre. </br>Begin again tomorrow.
  </p>

</article>
